ed by the cultural values of sports psychology; and how unequal power relations influence the ability of different groups of Aboriginal people to implement their own visions for sport. The diverse analyses illuminate how Aboriginal people employ sport as a venue through which to assert their cultural identities and find a positive space for themselves and upcoming generations in contemporary Canadian society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aIndigenous peoplesxSportszCanada. 0aIndigenous peopleszCanadaxSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh1 aCarpenter, Amy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForsyth, Janice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForsyth, Janice, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGiles, Audrey R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiles, Audrey R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHalas, Joannie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHall, M. Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeine, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLavallée, Lynn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLévesque, Lucie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcRae, Heather, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO’bonsawin, Christine M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aParaschak, Victoria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeltier, Duke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchinke, Robert J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/